<div id="subtree-container" class="subtree-container"><div class="aea2d7dde423afa7ad9351a0886150a8-scss b51b00c1669ad99a1c607cd1e77c2824-scss" style="inset: 384px 269px 0px 0px; justify-content: flex-end;"><div class="afeebf1df237d4103108ba40799802d6-scss"><div class="c13443431e58facf06f9d12490b92a82-scss" style="width: 90vw; max-width: 8.5in;"><div class="_0df5ec6b9902d7d22ccfa3ebb4f35211-scss">Integration with the Scope Module</div><div class="e5e059a27f4c194020f0d961a3cb5989-scss" dir="auto"><div class="fr-view"><p class="p1" data-pasted="true">This document helps us capture our AIR in plain language, but the actual <span class="s1"><strong>structured requirements</strong></span> including formats, units, delivery dates, and responsibilities are created and managed in the <span class="s1"><strong>Plannerly Scope module</strong></span>.</p>
<p class="p1">Once we’ve identified what operational data we need, we can:</p>
<ul class="froala-checkbox-list">
<li class="p1">
<strong>Create asset-specific information requirements</strong><span class="s1"> in Scope</span>
</li>
<li class="p1">
<span class="s1"><strong>Assign responsibility</strong></span> to the right team or supply chain partner</li>
<li class="p1">
<span class="s1"><strong>Define data formats</strong></span>, such as units (e.g., °C, kW, mm), expected values, or classifications</li>
<li class="p1">
<span class="s1"><strong>Map each property</strong></span> to standard COBie fields or IFC property sets</li>
<li class="p1">
<span class="s1"><strong>Set up verification logic</strong></span>, to check whether required data has been delivered</li>
<li class="p1">
<span class="s1"><strong>Track delivery status</strong></span>, approvals, and version history </li>
</ul>
<p>These structured AIR definitions ensure that our information can be exchanged, verified, and reused </p></div></div></div></div></div></div>